 [[Miami, Florida]].<ref>[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] {{google books|w2QEAAAAMBAJ|The Advocate, 15 October 2002|page=61}}</ref><ref>Steven Paul Davies {{google books|3NPjCwAAQBAJ|Out at the Movies: A History of Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transexual and Queer Cinema|page=283}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Yossi & Jagger]]'' || {{Sortname|Eytan|Fox}} || Israel || Romance, drama, war || [[Ohad Knoller]], [[Yehuda Levi]], [[Assi Cohen]], [[Aya Koren|Aya Steinovitz]], [[Hani Furstenberg]], Sharon Raginiano, [[Yuval Semo]], Yaniv Moyal, Hanan Savyon, Erez Kahana, Shmulik Bernheimer and Yael Pearl ||\n|-\n| ''[[You'll Get Over It]]'' || {{Sortname|Fabrice|Cazeneuve}} || France || Drama || Julien Baumgartner, Julia Maraval, [[J\u00e9r\u00e9mie Elka\u00efm]], Fran\u00e7ois Comar, Patrick Bonnel, Christiane Millet, [[Antoine Michel]], Nils Ohlund, [[Bernard Blancan]] and Eric Bonicatto ||a.k.a. ''\u00c0 cause d'un gar\u00e7on''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2002 films}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:LGBT-related films of 2002}}\n[[Category:2002 in LGBT history|Films]]\n[[Category:2002 films|*LGBT]]\n[[Category:Lists of LGBT-related films by year|2002]]\n[[Category:2002-related lists]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT-related films|*2002]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilms:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: , \u2192 , , 1977-1997 \u2192 1977\u20131997", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_LGBT-related_films_of_2002"}
{"title_page": "Oued Fes", "text_new": "[[File:ETH-BIB-Fluss in F\u00e8s-Nordafrikaflug 1932-LBS MH02-13-0368.tif|thumb|The Oued Bou Khareb (a part of the Oued Fes) flowing through the middle of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]], in a photograph from 1932.|alt=]]\nThe '''Oued Fes''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0641\u0627\u0633|lit=River of Fes}}) is a [[river]] in [[Morocco]]. It is a [[tributary]] of the [[Sebou River]] and historically the main source of water for the city of [[Fez, Morocco|Fes]], after which it is named.\n\nThe river consists of a number of different [[Stream|streams]] which originate in the Sa\u00efss Plain to the south and west of Fes before joining together in the area of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]], the old city ([[Medina quarter|medina]]) of Fes.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Le Tourneau|first=Roger|title=F\u00e8s avant le protectorat: \u00e9tude \u00e9conomique et sociale d'une ville de l'occident musulman|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Marocaine de Librairie et d'\u00c9dition|year=1949|isbn=|location=Casablanca|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\">{{Cite book|last=M\u00e9talsi|first=Mohamed|title=F\u00e8s: La ville essentielle|publisher=ACR \u00c9dition Internationale|year=2003|isbn=978-2867701528|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> Over the centuries the river has been split and diverted into a multitude of [[Canal|canals]] that distributed water across the city and once powered a number of historic [[Noria|waterwheels]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> After the river leaves the city it runs eastwards for a short distance before joining the Sebou River. The various branches and sections of the river, including many of the man-made canals, also have their own names.\n\n== Source ==\nThe river begins at Ras al-Ma (\"Head of the Water\"), 12 [[Kilometre|kilometres]] southwest of the city, from a hollow of [[Lake|lacustrine]] [[limestone]], with an approximate [[Discharge (hydrology)|flow]] of 500 [[Litre|litres]]/second.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Madani|first=Tariq|date=1999|title=Le r\u00e9seau hydraulique de la ville de F\u00e8s|url=|journal=Arch\u00e9ologie islamique|volume=8-9|pages=119-142|via=}}</ref>{{Rp|131}} \n\n== Oued al-Jawahir ==\n[[File:Oued Fes east of old mechouar (crop).png|thumb|View towards the Oued al-Jawahir's exit from under the walls of the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Old Mechouar (Vieux M\u00e9chouar)|Old Mechouar]] (through the arched openings at ground level seen in the distance). The first major division of the river takes place here. One of the canals (part of the Oued Fejjalin division) is seen on the left.|alt=]]\nThe main branch of the river skirts the northern edge of the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)|Royal Palace]] grounds (the ''Dar al-Makhzen'') and of [[Fes Jdid|Fes el-Jdid]] before entering [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]]. This section is also known as the ''Oued al-Jawahir'' ({{Lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0648\u0627\u0647\u0631|lit=River of Pearls}}).<ref name=\":02\" /> It once passed through a flat area of marshes and [[Wetland|wetlands]] located near what is now Fes el-Jdid and the modern ''Ville Nouvelle'', before emerging at a number places.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Gaudio|first=Attilio|title=F\u00e8s: Joyau de la civilisation islamique|publisher=Les Presse de l'UNESCO: Nouvelles \u00c9ditions Latines|year=1982|isbn=2723301591|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> However, since the founding of Fes el-Jdid (13th century), the Oued al-Jawahir was progressively diverted and some of its old streams seem to have disappeared.<ref name=\":6\" /> The river's flow was re-engineered to provide water for the Royal Palace complex and a succession of royal gardens such as the [[Fes Jdid#The Marinid Royal Gardens (Mosara Garden)|Mosara Gardens]] of the [[Marinid Sultanate|Marinids]] (now disappeared) and the 19th-century [[Jnan Sbil Gardens]] (still extant), before continuing towards Fes el-Bali, where it is distributed across an extensive network of man-made streams and canals.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> \n\n=== The historic water network of Fes el-Bali ===\nFes el-Bali's extensive water network predates the foundation of Fes el-Jdid. Its current outlines were begun by the [[Zenata]] [[emir]] Dounas ibn Hamama between 1137 and 1049, and then further elaborated by the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravid]] emir [[Yusuf ibn Tashfin|Yusuf ib Tashfin]] between 1069 (the Almoravid conquest of Fes) and 1106.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Marcos Cobaleda|first=Maria|last2=Villalba Sola|first2=Dolores|date=2018|title=Transformations in medieval Fez: Almoravid hydraulic system and changes in the Almohad walls|url=|journal=The Journal of North African Studies|volume=23 (4)|pages=591-623|via=}}</ref>  From the west, the Oued al-Jawahir flows eastward along the northern edge of Fes el-Jdid, passing through the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Bab Bou Jat Mechouar|Bab Bou Jat Mechouar]], through the [[Dar al-Makina]] (a former arms factory), and then beneath the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Old Mechouar (Vieux M\u00e9chouar)|Old Mechouar]] near [[Bab Dekkakin]] before reemerging on its eastern side, on the edge of the Jnan Sbil Gardens. Here it emerges from four arched openings at the bottom of the Old Mechouar's [[Rampart (fortification)|ramparts]] and the first major man-made division of the river take place.<ref name=\":3\" /> This division creates a number of canals (many of them hidden under streets and houses) through Fes el-Bali which eventually spill back into the Oued Bou Khareb (the name of the river's main course inside the city).<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> There are four main historic canal divisions: the ''Oued Fejjalin'', the ''Oued el-Hamiya'', the ''Sakiyyat el-Abbasa'', and the ''Oued Shrashar''.<ref name=\":02\" /> Most of these then split off into other canals as they progress through the city.\n[[File:\u062c\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0628\u064a\u0644.jpg|thumb|A historic ''[[noria]]'' (waterwheel) located on the western edge of the [[Jnan Sbil Gardens]] between [[Fes Jdid|Fes el-Jdid]] and [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]].|alt=]]\nThe Oued Fejjalin is one of the most important divisions and from it the ''Oued el-Lemtiyyin'' also splits off to supply the northernmost parts of the city.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> The Oued el-Lemtiyyin passes under the [[Bab Bou Jeloud|Bou Jeloud]] area and travels under the houses of [[Tala'a Kebira]] street until it reaches the [[Bou Inania Madrasa]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Here, in the vicinity of the madrasa, the water is collected by a large distributor structure made of brick and rammed and dating from the Almoravid period. This structure has three arched openings that lead into vaulted chambers from which the water emerges on the other side into three canals at different elevations, which then spread across different parts of the northern city.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAs for the Oued el-Hamiya, it splits from the other major branches at Jnan Sbil before dividing into more branches which mostly supply the southern parts of the city.<ref name=\":3\" /> One of its branches also once supplied, via an aqueduct, the [[Andalusian Mosque|Andalus]] quarter on the opposite shore of the Bou Khareb river.<ref name=\":02\" /> (Most of the water for the Andalus quarter, however, came from a canal which originated from other streams to the south of instead of the Oued al-Jawahir; see \"Oued Masmuda\" section below.) The two last branches, Sakiyyat al-Abbasa and the Oued Shrashar, supplied the regions near [[Gates of Fez|Bab al-Hadid]] and the gardens between Fes el-Jdid and Fes el-Bali.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nMany of these canals are now underground, with only some ancient [[Toponymy|toponyms]] hinting at former bridges that passed over them (e.g. the name ''Qantrat Bou Rous'' along a part of [[Tala'a Kebira]]).<ref name=\":02\" /> These canals and streams also feed a number of industries such as the historic [[Tanning (leather)|tanneries]] of the city, the most famous of which are the [[Chouara Tannery|Chouara Tanneries]].<ref name=\":02\" /> A large number of [[Water wheel|waterwheels]] (known as ''[[noria]]''s or sometimes as ''saqiyya''s) were located throughout the city's water network in order to assist in water distribution or to power certain industries.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Some of these were very large, such as the huge noria which supplied the Marinid royal gardens of Mosara, measuring 26 meters in diameter and 2 meters in thickness.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /> Only a few of these waterwheels have survived in some form, including some examples around the Jnan Sbil Gardens.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Oued Bou Khareb ==\n[[File:Oued Bou Khareb.jpg|thumb|Oued Bou Khareb in 2010.|alt=]]\n''Oued Bou Khareb'' (or sometimes ''Oued el-Kbir'') is the usual name given to the main urban course of the river through the middle of Fes el-Bali.<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|122}} This river is initially fed by two other streams called the ''Oued ez-Zitoun'' and the ''Oued Bou Fekran'' that enter the city from the south at [[Gates of Fez|Bab Jdid]].<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|234}} It is also fed by the various canals that split off from the Oued al-Jawahir to supply the city before eventually ending up in this ravine in the middle of the city. As the lowest point in the medina, the river thus acts as a collector for the city's used water.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />  \n\nThe course of the Bou Khareb also forms the historical boundary between the [[University of al-Qarawiyyin|Qarawiyyin]] and [[Andalusian Mosque|Andalus]] quarters of the city, which were originally two separate cities (''al-'Aliya'' and ''Madinat Fas'') in their early history before being joined together by the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravids]] in the 11th century.<ref name=\":02\" /> Much of the Oued Bou Khareb's course, from Bab Jdid to [[R'cif Mosque|Place R'cif]], is now hidden beneath a modern road for car traffic (one of the few that penetrates the medina). The road covers the river up to Place R'cif, a large square at the heart of the medina, and the river reemerges on the north side of square.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> From there the river runs northeast and exits the city between [[Bab Guissa]] and the former gate of Bab Sidi Bou Jida.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n=== Oued Masmuda ===\nThe streams to the south of the city which formed the beginning of the Bou Khareb river also fed another important canal called ''Oued Masmuda''.<ref name=\":02\" /> This canal, slightly further east, supplied water for most of the Andalus quarter of Fes on the southeast side of the Bou Khareb river.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> It begins to the south of the city and passed through the old city walls through a [[culvert]] opening called ''Bab ash-Shobbak'' (\"Gate of the Window\") which was protected by an iron [[grille]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> A few other canals split from it as it wound its way through the city, until it finally rejoined the Bou Khareb river shortly before its exit from the city.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The canal appears to be named after the [[Masmuda]] [[Berbers|Berber]] tribal confederacy that founded the [[Almohad Caliphate|Almohad movement]], which suggests that it might have been constructed by the Almohads or that Masmuda families or troops were housed near it at some point.<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|113}}\n\n=== Historic Bridges over the Bou Khareb ===\n[[File:ETH-BIB-Br\u00fccke in F\u00e8s-Nordafrikaflug 1932-LBS MH02-13-0385.tif|thumb|The Terrafin Bridge (\"Bridge of the Cobblers\") over the river in 1932. Today the bridge is located at the northern edge of Place R'cif.]]\nThe Oued Bou Khareb is crossed by several historic bridges inside the medina, some of which were first built before the unification of the two shores into a single city in the 11th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://visitefes.com/la-magnifique-renovation-des-27-monuments-de-fes/|title=La magnifique r\u00e9novation des 27 monuments de F\u00e8s \u2013 Conseil R\u00e9gional du Tourisme (CRT) de F\u00e8s|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> There were once at least six bridges, reportedly built by the [[Zenata]] [[emir]] Dounas ibn Hamama in the early 11th century, before the unification of the two cities by the Almoravids later in the same century.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Gaillard|first=Henri|title=Une ville de l'Islam: F\u00e8s|publisher=J. Andr\u00e9|year=1905|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=32}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Other scholarly sources, however, attribute at least some of the bridges to the Almoravid period (late 11th to early 12th centuries) when the two early cities of Fes were unified.<ref name=\":4\" /> Many of them were destroyed in subsequent floods in the early 14th century, and only some of them were rebuilt by the Marinid Sultan [[Abu Sa'id Uthman II|Abu Sa'id]] at the time.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOf the bridges that remain today, the ''Qantra Bin el-Moudoun'' (\"Bridge Between the Two Cities\") is the northernmost of them, followed to the south by the ''Qantrat Sebbaghin'' (\"Bridge of the Tanners\") and by the ''Qantrat Terrafin'' (\"Bridge of the Cobblers\") just north of Place R'cif. Another bridge, the Bridge of Sidi al-'Awwad, was located further south but likely disappeared during the 20th century when the river was covered by the modern paved road.<ref name=\":02\" /> The Bin el-Moudoun Bridge, believed to date from the time of Emir Dounas ibn Hamama, was considered one of the most picturesque, being located amidst a stretch of rocky [[rapids]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> It has a span composed of three arches but only the central one is still visible today.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Sebbaghin Bridge, also known as the ''Khrashfiyin'' Bridge (or ''Khrachfiyine'' in the [[French language|French]] [[transliteration]]), is believed to have been originally built by Emir Dounas and restored or rebuilt by the Marinids in the 14th century.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> The Terrafin bridge, originally named ''Qantrat Bab al-Silsila'' and now found on the northern edge of Place R'cif, is also believed to date initially from Emir Dounas in the 11th century.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> It is notable for having been lined with shops on both sides, a feature still visible in its structure today.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Pollution problems and rehabilitation efforts ==\n[[File:Fes, Old city.jpg|thumb|Traditional [[Tanning (leather)|tanners]] are seen working along the Oued Bou Khareb (2006; before recent renovations to the area).|alt=|left]]\n{{multiple image\n | width = 220\n | direction = vertical\n | image1 = Fes bridge restoration 1.jpg\n | image2 = Fes bridge restoration 3.jpg\n | footer = The Sebbaghin or Khrashfiyin Bridge at the beginning of restoration (November 2014) and after restoration (2015).\n}}\nThe river, particularly the Oued Bou Khareb within the old medina, had long suffered from heavy pollution due to [[sewage]], the activities of the nearby tanneries (which generate chemical waste), and to being used as a dumping ground by residents.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcitiesdive.com/ex/sustainablecitiescollective/revitalization-fez-river-reclaimed-public-space/171636/|title=Revitalization of the Fez River: A Reclaimed Public Space {{!}} Smart Cities Dive|website=www.smartcitiesdive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.morocco.com/blog/the-rejuvenation-of-the-fez-river/|title=Morocco.com {{!}} The Rejuvenation of the Fez River|website=www.morocco.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Even the name Oued Bou Khareb means \"River of Trash\".<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In recent times the city authorities had begun covering the exposed parts of the river with concrete slabs, which only led to more garbage piling up.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the late 2000s, a large-scale project to rehabilitate the river system and its urban environment was begun. The project, led by architect [[Aziza Chaouni]], included the cleaning up of the river, the renovation of its urban shoreline, the creation of open pedestrian walkways, and the renovation of existing open spaces along the river such Place R'cif and Place Lalla Yeddouna.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daniels.utoronto.ca/news/2014/03/20/aziza-chaouni-presents-2014-ted-talk-her-efforts-uncover-fez-river-morocco|title=Aziza Chaouni presents a 2014 TED Talk on her efforts to uncover the Fez River in Morocco|date=2014-03-20|website=Daniels|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The proposal to improve water quality also included the creation of wetlands (which had previously existed along the river's course) and the restoration of the river's canals.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe rehabilitation of the river, which has been underway since, also took place alongside broader efforts to restore the historical monuments and landmarks of the old city, mostly under the direction of the local heritage restoration agency ADER-Fes. This included the restoration of the bridges over the Bou Khareb river, with the Terrafin and Sebbaghin/Khrashfiyin bridges being restored in the 2010s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Fes}}\n\n{{coord|34|04|53.8|N|4|55|21.5|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Morocco]]\n[[category:Fez, Morocco]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:ETH-BIB-Fluss in F\u00e8s-Nordafrikaflug 1932-LBS MH02-13-0368.tif|thumb|The Oued Bou Khareb (a part of the Oued Fes) flowing through the middle of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]], in a photograph from 1932.|alt=]]\nThe '''Oued Fes''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0641\u0627\u0633|lit=River of Fes}}) is a [[river]] in [[Morocco]]. It is a [[tributary]] of the [[Sebou River]] and historically the main source of water for the city of [[Fez, Morocco|Fes]], after which it is named.\n\nThe river consists of a number of different [[Stream|streams]] which originate in the Sa\u00efss Plain to the south and west of Fes before joining together in the area of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]], the old city ([[Medina quarter|medina]]) of Fes.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Le Tourneau|first=Roger|title=F\u00e8s avant le protectorat: \u00e9tude \u00e9conomique et sociale d'une ville de l'occident musulman|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Marocaine de Librairie et d'\u00c9dition|year=1949|isbn=|location=Casablanca|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\">{{Cite book|last=M\u00e9talsi|first=Mohamed|title=F\u00e8s: La ville essentielle|publisher=ACR \u00c9dition Internationale|year=2003|isbn=978-2867701528|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> Over the centuries the river has been split and diverted into a multitude of [[Canal|canals]] that distributed water across the city and once powered a number of historic [[Noria|waterwheels]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> After the river leaves the city it runs eastwards for a short distance before joining the Sebou River. The various branches and sections of the river, including many of the man-made canals, also have their own names.\n\n== Source ==\nThe river begins at Ras al-Ma (\"Head of the Water\"), 12 [[Kilometre|kilometres]] southwest of the city, from a hollow of [[Lake|lacustrine]] [[limestone]], with an approximate [[Discharge (hydrology)|flow]] of 500 [[Litre|litres]]/second.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Madani|first=Tariq|date=1999|title=Le r\u00e9seau hydraulique de la ville de F\u00e8s|url=|journal=Arch\u00e9ologie islamique|volume=8-9|pages=119-142|via=}}</ref>{{Rp|131}} \n\n== Oued al-Jawahir ==\n[[File:Oued Fes east of old mechouar (crop).png|thumb|View towards the Oued al-Jawahir's exit from under the walls of the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Old Mechouar (Vieux M\u00e9chouar)|Old Mechouar]] (through the arched openings at ground level seen in the distance). The first major division of the river takes place here. One of the canals (part of the Oued Fejjalin division) is seen on the left.|alt=]]\nThe main branch of the river skirts the northern edge of the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)|Royal Palace]] grounds (the ''Dar al-Makhzen'') and of [[Fes Jdid|Fes el-Jdid]] before entering [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]]. This section is also known as the ''Oued al-Jawahir'' ({{Lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0648\u0627\u0647\u0631|lit=River of Pearls}}).<ref name=\":02\" /> It once passed through a flat area of marshes and [[Wetland|wetlands]] located near what is now Fes el-Jdid and the modern ''Ville Nouvelle'', before emerging at a number places.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Gaudio|first=Attilio|title=F\u00e8s: Joyau de la civilisation islamique|publisher=Les Presse de l'UNESCO: Nouvelles \u00c9ditions Latines|year=1982|isbn=2723301591|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> However, since the founding of Fes el-Jdid (13th century), the Oued al-Jawahir was progressively diverted and some of its old streams seem to have disappeared.<ref name=\":6\" /> The river's flow was re-engineered to provide water for the Royal Palace complex and a succession of royal gardens such as the [[Fes Jdid#The Marinid Royal Gardens (Mosara Garden)|Mosara Gardens]] of the [[Marinid Sultanate|Marinids]] (now disappeared) and the 19th-century [[Jnan Sbil Gardens]] (still extant), before continuing towards Fes el-Bali, where it is distributed across an extensive network of man-made streams and canals.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> \n\n=== The historic water network of Fes el-Bali ===\nFes el-Bali's extensive water network predates the foundation of Fes el-Jdid. Its current outlines were begun by the [[Zenata]] [[emir]] Dounas ibn Hamama between 1137 and 1049, and then further elaborated by the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravid]] emir [[Yusuf ibn Tashfin|Yusuf ib Tashfin]] between 1069 (the Almoravid conquest of Fes) and 1106.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Marcos Cobaleda|first=Maria|last2=Villalba Sola|first2=Dolores|date=2018|title=Transformations in medieval Fez: Almoravid hydraulic system and changes in the Almohad walls|url=|journal=The Journal of North African Studies|volume=23 (4)|pages=591-623|via=}}</ref>  From the west, the Oued al-Jawahir flows eastward along the northern edge of Fes el-Jdid, passing through the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Bab Bou Jat Mechouar|Bab Bou Jat Mechouar]], through the [[Dar al-Makina]] (a former arms factory), and then beneath the [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)#Old Mechouar (Vieux M\u00e9chouar)|Old Mechouar]] near [[Bab Dekkakin]] before reemerging on its eastern side, on the edge of the Jnan Sbil Gardens. Here it emerges from four arched openings at the bottom of the Old Mechouar's [[Rampart (fortification)|ramparts]] and the first major man-made division of the river take place.<ref name=\":3\" /> This division creates a number of canals (many of them hidden under streets and houses) through Fes el-Bali which eventually spill back into the Oued Bou Khareb (the name of the river's main course inside the city).<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> There are four main historic canal divisions: the ''Oued Fejjalin'', the ''Oued el-Hamiya'', the ''Sakiyyat el-Abbasa'', and the ''Oued Shrashar''.<ref name=\":02\" /> Most of these then split off into other canals as they progress through the city.\n[[File:\u062c\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0628\u064a\u0644.jpg|thumb|A historic ''[[noria]]'' (waterwheel) located on the western edge of the [[Jnan Sbil Gardens]] between [[Fes Jdid|Fes el-Jdid]] and [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]].|alt=]]\nThe Oued Fejjalin is one of the most important divisions and from it the ''Oued el-Lemtiyyin'' also splits off to supply the northernmost parts of the city.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> The Oued el-Lemtiyyin passes under the [[Bab Bou Jeloud|Bou Jeloud]] area and travels under the houses of [[Tala'a Kebira]] street until it reaches the [[Bou Inania Madrasa]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Here, in the vicinity of the madrasa, the water is collected by a large distributor structure made of brick and rammed and dating from the Almoravid period. This structure has three arched openings that lead into vaulted chambers from which the water emerges on the other side into three canals at different elevations, which then spread across different parts of the northern city.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAs for the Oued el-Hamiya, it splits from the other major branches at Jnan Sbil before dividing into more branches which mostly supply the southern parts of the city.<ref name=\":3\" /> One of its branches also once supplied, via an aqueduct, the [[Andalusian Mosque|Andalus]] quarter on the opposite shore of the Bou Khareb river.<ref name=\":02\" /> (Most of the water for the Andalus quarter, however, came from a canal which originated from other streams to the south of instead of the Oued al-Jawahir; see \"Oued Masmuda\" section below.) The two last branches, Sakiyyat al-Abbasa and the Oued Shrashar, supplied the regions near [[Gates of Fez|Bab al-Hadid]] and the gardens between Fes el-Jdid and Fes el-Bali.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nMany of these canals are now underground, with only some ancient [[Toponymy|toponyms]] hinting at former bridges that passed over them (e.g. the name ''Qantrat Bou Rous'' along a part of [[Tala'a Kebira]]).<ref name=\":02\" /> These canals and streams also feed a number of industries such as the historic [[Tanning (leather)|tanneries]] of the city, the most famous of which are the [[Chouara Tannery|Chouara Tanneries]].<ref name=\":02\" /> A large number of [[Water wheel|waterwheels]] (known as ''[[noria]]''s or sometimes as ''saqiyya''s) were located throughout the city's water network in order to assist in water distribution or to power certain industries.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Some of these were very large, such as the huge noria which supplied the Marinid royal gardens of Mosara, measuring 26 meters in diameter and 2 meters in thickness.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /> Only a few of these waterwheels have survived in some form, including some examples around the Jnan Sbil Gardens.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Oued Bou Khareb ==\n[[File:Oued Bou Khareb.jpg|thumb|Oued Bou Khareb in 2010.|alt=]]\n''Oued Bou Khareb'' (or sometimes ''Oued el-Kbir'') is the usual name given to the main urban course of the river through the middle of Fes el-Bali.<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|122}} This river is initially fed by two other streams called the ''Oued ez-Zitoun'' and the ''Oued Bou Fekran'' that enter the city from the south at [[Gates of Fez|Bab Jdid]].<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|234}} It is also fed by the various canals that split off from the Oued al-Jawahir to supply the city before eventually ending up in this ravine in the middle of the city. As the lowest point in the medina, the river thus acts as a collector for the city's used water.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />  \n\nThe course of the Bou Khareb also forms the historical boundary between the [[University of al-Qarawiyyin|Qarawiyyin]] and [[Andalusian Mosque|Andalus]] quarters of the city, which were originally two separate cities (''al-'Aliya'' and ''Madinat Fas'') in their early history before being joined together by the [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravids]] in the 11th century.<ref name=\":02\" /> Much of the Oued Bou Khareb's course, from Bab Jdid to [[R'cif Mosque|Place R'cif]], is now hidden beneath a modern road for car traffic (one of the few that penetrates the medina). The road covers the river up to Place R'cif, a large square at the heart of the medina, and the river reemerges on the north side of square.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> From there the river runs northeast and exits the city between [[Bab Guissa]] and the former gate of Bab Sidi Bou Jida.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n=== Oued Masmuda ===\nThe streams to the south of the city which formed the beginning of the Bou Khareb river also fed another important canal called ''Oued Masmuda''.<ref name=\":02\" /> This canal, slightly further east, supplied water for most of the Andalus quarter of Fes on the southeast side of the Bou Khareb river.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> It begins to the south of the city and passed through the old city walls through a [[culvert]] opening called ''Bab ash-Shobbak'' (\"Gate of the Window\") which was protected by an iron [[grille]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> A few other canals split from it as it wound its way through the city, until it finally rejoined the Bou Khareb river shortly before its exit from the city.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The canal appears to be named after the [[Masmuda]] [[Berber]] tribal confederacy that founded the [[Almohad Caliphate|Almohad movement]], which suggests that it might have been constructed by the Almohads or that Masmuda families or troops were housed near it at some point.<ref name=\":02\" />{{Rp|113}}\n\n=== Historic Bridges over the Bou Khareb ===\n[[File:ETH-BIB-Br\u00fccke in F\u00e8s-Nordafrikaflug 1932-LBS MH02-13-0385.tif|thumb|The Terrafin Bridge (\"Bridge of the Cobblers\") over the river in 1932. Today the bridge is located at the northern edge of Place R'cif.]]\nThe Oued Bou Khareb is crossed by several historic bridges inside the medina, some of which were first built before the unification of the two shores into a single city in the 11th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://visitefes.com/la-magnifique-renovation-des-27-monuments-de-fes/|title=La magnifique r\u00e9novation des 27 monuments de F\u00e8s \u2013 Conseil R\u00e9gional du Tourisme (CRT) de F\u00e8s|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> There were once at least six bridges, reportedly built by the [[Zenata]] [[emir]] Dounas ibn Hamama in the early 11th century, before the unification of the two cities by the Almoravids later in the same century.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Gaillard|first=Henri|title=Une ville de l'Islam: F\u00e8s|publisher=J. Andr\u00e9|year=1905|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=32}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Other scholarly sources, however, attribute at least some of the bridges to the Almoravid period (late 11th to early 12th centuries) when the two early cities of Fes were unified.<ref name=\":4\" /> Many of them were destroyed in subsequent floods in the early 14th century, and only some of them were rebuilt by the Marinid Sultan [[Abu Sa'id Uthman II|Abu Sa'id]] at the time.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOf the bridges that remain today, the ''Qantra Bin el-Moudoun'' (\"Bridge Between the Two Cities\") is the northernmost of them, followed to the south by the ''Qantrat Sebbaghin'' (\"Bridge of the Tanners\") and by the ''Qantrat Terrafin'' (\"Bridge of the Cobblers\") just north of Place R'cif. Another bridge, the Bridge of Sidi al-'Awwad, was located further south but likely disappeared during the 20th century when the river was covered by the modern paved road.<ref name=\":02\" /> The Bin el-Moudoun Bridge, believed to date from the time of Emir Dounas ibn Hamama, was considered one of the most picturesque, being located amidst a stretch of rocky [[rapids]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> It has a span composed of three arches but only the central one is still visible today.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Sebbaghin Bridge, also known as the ''Khrashfiyin'' Bridge (or ''Khrachfiyine'' in the [[French language|French]] [[transliteration]]), is believed to have been originally built by Emir Dounas and restored or rebuilt by the Marinids in the 14th century.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> The Terrafin bridge, originally named ''Qantrat Bab al-Silsila'' and now found on the northern edge of Place R'cif, is also believed to date initially from Emir Dounas in the 11th century.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> It is notable for having been lined with shops on both sides, a feature still visible in its structure today.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Pollution problems and rehabilitation efforts ==\n[[File:Fes, Old city.jpg|thumb|Traditional [[Tanning (leather)|tanners]] are seen working along the Oued Bou Khareb (2006; before recent renovations to the area).|alt=|left]]\n{{multiple image\n | width = 220\n | direction = vertical\n | image1 = Fes bridge restoration 1.jpg\n | image2 = Fes bridge restoration 3.jpg\n | footer = The Sebbaghin or Khrashfiyin Bridge at the beginning of restoration (November 2014) and after restoration (2015).\n}}\nThe river, particularly the Oued Bou Khareb within the old medina, had long suffered from heavy pollution due to [[sewage]], the activities of the nearby tanneries (which generate chemical waste), and to being used as a dumping ground by residents.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smartcitiesdive.com/ex/sustainablecitiescollective/revitalization-fez-river-reclaimed-public-space/171636/|title=Revitalization of the Fez River: A Reclaimed Public Space {{!}} Smart Cities Dive|website=www.smartcitiesdive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.morocco.com/blog/the-rejuvenation-of-the-fez-river/|title=Morocco.com {{!}} The Rejuvenation of the Fez River|website=www.morocco.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Even the name Oued Bou Khareb means \"River of Trash\".<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In recent times the city authorities had begun covering the exposed parts of the river with concrete slabs, which only led to more garbage piling up.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn the late 2000s, a large-scale project to rehabilitate the river system and its urban environment was begun. The project, led by architect [[Aziza Chaouni]], included the cleaning up of the river, the renovation of its urban shoreline, the creation of open pedestrian walkways, and the renovation of existing open spaces along the river such Place R'cif and Place Lalla Yeddouna.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daniels.utoronto.ca/news/2014/03/20/aziza-chaouni-presents-2014-ted-talk-her-efforts-uncover-fez-river-morocco|title=Aziza Chaouni presents a 2014 TED Talk on her efforts to uncover the Fez River in Morocco|date=2014-03-20|website=Daniels|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The proposal to improve water quality also included the creation of wetlands (which had previously existed along the river's course) and the restoration of the river's canals.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe rehabilitation of the river, which has been underway since, also took place alongside broader efforts to restore the historical monuments and landmarks of the old city, mostly under the direction of the local heritage restoration agency ADER-Fes. This included the restoration of the bridges over the Bou Khareb river, with the Terrafin and Sebbaghin/Khrashfiyin bridges being restored in the 2010s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Fes}}\n\n{{coord|34|04|53.8|N|4|55|21.5|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Morocco]]\n[[category:Fez, Morocco]]\n", "name_user": "Robert Prazeres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOued Masmuda", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oued_Fes"}
